\par \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 Resource Management
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 ----------------------------------
\par 
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 
C# provides automatic garbage collection.  The garbage collector (GC) keeps track of how many references (pointers) exist for each object.  When an object no longer has any references, the GC will eventually delete the object.  When the GC deletes the obj
\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 e\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 ct, it calls the object's destructor.  
\par 
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 The GC calls destructors in a special garbage collection thread, so destructors can not interact with opengl, because all calls to opengl must be made from a single thread.  (There are ways around this, but I believ
\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 
e they are inefficient, so we will not pursue them.)  This situation is also the case with the FMOD sound system, and is probably true with OpenAL as well, but I haven't verified this yet.  Therefore, we can not free opengl and sound system resources from
\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1  \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 
within destructors.  According to my reading, the standard way to dispose of "unmanaged resources" (resources allocated by unmanaged code) is to use the IDisposable interface.  Classes that contain unmanaged resources that ought to be released (such as te
\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 x\hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 tures, display lists and sound samples) should implement the IDisposable interface, which has a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs20\insrsid14116422 \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 
 single method called Dispose.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\fs20\insrsid1531720 
\par 
\par \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 Currently, the code releases graphics resources by calling the Dispose method of IDisposable objects.  However, we have yet to \hich\af1\dbch\af12\loch\f1 
define a comprehensive management system for textures and display lists (and possibly other graphics resources, such as shaders).  We may want to dispense with IDisposable if we come up with a better solution in the near future.
\par 
